diagnoses.name: Chronic Fatigue Syndrome
diagnoses.description: A complex disorder characterized by extreme fatigue, non-restorative sleep, and multiple symptoms including muscle pain, multi-joint pain without redness or swelling, enlarged lymph nodes, sore throat, and headaches. The cause is unknown.

diagnoses.name: Sjögren's Syndrome
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disorder identified by its two most common symptoms — dry eyes and a dry mouth. Sjögren's syndrome often accompanies other immune system disorders, such as rheumatoid arthritis and lupus. Symptoms include irritated eyes and decreased appetite.

diagnoses.name: Hyperthyroidism
diagnoses.description: The overproduction of a hormone by the butterfly-shaped gland in the neck (thyroid). Symptoms can include weight loss, increased appetite (though decreased appetite can occur in some individuals), sweating, and, in some severe cases, osteopenia.

diagnoses.name: Addison's Disease
diagnoses.description: A disorder that occurs when your body produces insufficient amounts of certain hormones produced by your adrenal glands. Symptoms include fatigue, weight loss, decreased appetite, and easy bruising.

diagnoses.name: Celiac Disease
diagnoses.description: An immune reaction to eating gluten, a protein found in wheat, barley, and rye. Over time, the immune reaction to eating gluten creates inflammation that damages the small intestine's lining. Symptoms can include weight loss and fatigue due to malabsorption.

diagnoses.name: Rheumatoid Arthritis
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disorder that can affect more than just your joints. In some people, the condition can damage a wide variety of body systems, including the skin, eyes, lungs, heart, and blood vessels. Osteopenia can occur due to decreased mobility or corticosteroid use.

diagnoses.name: Lupus
diagnoses.description: A systemic autoimmune disease that occurs when your body's immune system attacks your own tissues and organs. Symptoms include fatigue, joint pain, rash, and fever. Chronic inflammation can lead to body tissue damage, affecting multiple organs and systems.

diagnoses.name: Ehlers-Danlos Syndromes
diagnoses.description: A group of disorders that affect connective tissues supporting the skin, bones, blood vessels, and many other organs and tissues. Symptoms may include soft, stretchy skin that bruises easily.

diagnoses.name: Iron Deficiency Anemia
diagnoses.description: A common type of anemia, a condition in which blood lacks adequate healthy red blood cells. Symptoms can include fatigue and diminished appetite.

diagnoses.name: Fibromyalgia
diagnoses.description: A disorder characterized by widespread musculoskeletal pain accompanied by fatigue, sleep, memory, and mood issues. Researchers believe fibromyalgia amplifies painful sensations by affecting the way your brain processes pain signals.

diagnoses.name: Chronic Myelomonocytic Leukemia
diagnoses.reasoning: Monocytosis, a key symptom, fits this rare type of leukemia that affects the blood and bone marrow.

diagnoses.name: Systemic Lupus Erythematosus
diagnoses.reasoning: This autoimmune disease can lead to a wide range of symptoms including decreased appetite and, less commonly, periodontal disease.

diagnoses.name: Rheumatoid Arthritis
diagnoses.reasoning: Chronic inflammatory disorder that can lead to systemic symptoms such as decreased appetite and monocytosis.

diagnoses.name: Anemia of Chronic Disease
diagnoses.reasoning: This condition is often seen with chronic diseases, manifesting in reduced appetite and elevated monocytes.

diagnoses.name: Sjögren's Syndrome
diagnoses.reasoning: An autoimmune condition that often presents with mouth dryness leading to periodontal disease, and can cause systemic issues like decreased appetite.

diagnoses.name: Chronic Kidney Disease
diagnoses.reasoning: Interstitial cystitis can sometimes be related to underlying chronic kidney issues, and CKD can cause decreased appetite and affect blood cell counts.

diagnoses.name: HIV/AIDS
diagnoses.reasoning: HIV can cause a variety of symptoms including monocytosis, decreased appetite, and is associated with periodontal disease.

diagnoses.name: Vitamin B12 Deficiency
diagnoses.reasoning: This deficiency can lead to decreased appetite and can indirectly cause monocytosis due to its effect on blood production.

diagnoses.name: Hypothyroidism
diagnoses.reasoning: Can cause decreased appetite and attention deficit. Though not directly causing interstitial cystitis or monocytosis, it affects overall body systems.

diagnoses.name: Depression
diagnoses.reasoning: While primarily affecting mental health, it can manifest physically as decreased appetite and attention deficit. The other symptoms could be indirectly related due to overall diminished health.

diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disorder where the ingestion of gluten leads to damage in the small intestine, potentially causing delayed puberty, ulcers, and anemia.
A type of inflammatory bowel disease (IBD) that may cause ulcers, delayed puberty due to malnutrition, and anemia.
Another form of IBD, causing ulcers in the digestive tract and possibly leading to anemia and delayed puberty from malnutrition.
A condition caused by lack of iron, which can lead to anemia, causing delayed puberty and potential for oral ulcers.
A rare genetic disorder that can cause tumors and cysts throughout the body, associated with flushing and can lead to hearing loss.
A rare genetic disorder characterized by spotty skin pigmentation, endocrine overactivity, and myxomas; it can cause flushing and is potentially related to delayed puberty.
A disorder that affects the endocrine glands, leading to symptoms such as tumors, ulcers due to increased stomach acid, and potentially anemia.
A genetic condition characterized by the development of polyps in the intestines and pigmented spots on the skin, which could lead to anemia and has been associated with delayed puberty.
An autoimmune disorder in children causing inflammation, which may result in delayed puberty, anemia, and also could potentially affect hearing.
An inherited condition that usually affects people of Mediterranean origin and causes recurrent fevers and painful inflammation of the abdomen, lungs, and joints, potentially leading to anemia.

diagnoses.name: Diabetes Mellitus
diagnoses.reasoning: Uncontrolled diabetes can lead to periodontal disease due to elevated blood glucose levels, which promote gum infection. It can also cause weight loss when glucose is not properly used for energy, and in advanced cases, may contribute to irritability.

diagnoses.name: Chronic Sinusitis
diagnoses.reasoning: Chronic sinusitis can cause post-nasal drip and oral pain due to the close proximity of sinus tissues to oral structures. It might also contribute to irritability due to chronic discomfort.

diagnoses.name: Gastroesophageal Reflux Disease (GERD)
diagnoses.reasoning: GERD can lead to oral pain from the acid reflux irritating the throat and mouth, and the constant irritation can cause post-nasal drip and irritability.

diagnoses.name: HIV/AIDS
diagnoses.reasoning: HIV/AIDS can lead to periodontal disease due to the weakening of the immune system. Weight loss is also a common symptom in advanced HIV infection.

diagnoses.name: Hyperthyroidism
diagnoses.reasoning: Hyperthyroidism can cause weight loss and irritability due to increased metabolism. It can indirectly contribute to periodontal disease through its effect on the immune system.

diagnoses.name: Sjögren's Syndrome
diagnoses.reasoning: Sjögren's Syndrome can lead to oral pain due to dry mouth, a hallmark symptom of the condition, and it can complicate periodontal disease due to decreased saliva production.

diagnoses.name: Bulimia Nervosa
diagnoses.reasoning: The recurrent binge-and-purge cycles can lead to oral pain and periodontal disease due to the acid erosion of teeth and gums. Weight loss is another significant symptom.

diagnoses.name: Depression
diagnoses.reasoning: Depression can indirectly lead to oral health issues due to neglect of personal hygiene. It's closely associated with irritability, and significant weight changes (loss or gain) are common symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Nutritional deficiencies (e.g., Vitamin B12, Vitamin D)
diagnoses.reasoning: Deficiencies in essential vitamins can lead to periodontal disease due to weakened immune defenses, and can cause oral pain due to the development of mouth ulcers. Weight loss might occur due to malabsorption or poor diet.

diagnoses.name: Substance Abuse
diagnoses.reasoning: Substances like tobacco and certain drugs can contribute to periodontal disease and oral pain. Weight loss and irritability can be direct or indirect effects of substance abuse.

diagnoses.name: Postural Orthostatic Tachycardia Syndrome (POTS)
diagnoses.description: A condition characterized by a significant increase in heart rate upon standing, often accompanied by symptoms like lightheadedness, fainting, and rapid heartbeat. POTS can be associated with mood changes, fatigue, and sometimes neurological symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Anxiety Disorders
diagnoses.description: Anxiety can manifest with physical symptoms such as tachycardia, restlessness, and can also affect concentration, causing mood lability and attentional difficulties.

diagnoses.name: Hereditary Angioedema
diagnoses.description: A rare genetic condition that causes episodes of severe swelling in various body parts, including the limbs, face, intestinal tract, and airway. It sometimes occurs alongside other systemic symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Iron Deficiency Anemia
diagnoses.description: A common condition resulting from low iron levels, which can lead to restless legs syndrome, fatigue, and could potentially exacerbate attention deficit issues due to decreased oxygenation.

diagnoses.name: Multiple Sclerosis (MS)
diagnoses.description: A chronic autoimmune disease affecting the central nervous system, potentially leading to a wide range of symptoms including mood lability, fatigue, orthostatic intolerance, and neurological unrest.

diagnoses.name: Thyroid Disorder (Hyperthyroidism/Hypothyroidism)
diagnoses.description: Thyroid dysfunctions can cause a broad spectrum of symptoms, including mood swings, cognitive difficulties, and can indirectly contribute to conditions like POTS.

diagnoses.name: Fibromyalgia
diagnoses.description: A long-term condition that causes pain all over the body, sleep problems, fatigue, and often coexists with conditions of mood disturbances and cognitive dysfunction.

diagnoses.name: Depression
diagnoses.description: Beyond affecting mood, depression can significantly impact physical health, contributing to phenomena like restless legs syndrome, attention deficits, and exacerbating symptoms of POTS through psychosomatic pathways.

diagnoses.name: Ehlers-Danlos Syndromes
diagnoses.description: A group of disorders that affect connective tissues and can manifest in a wide variety of symptoms including joint hypermobility, skin hyperextensibility, vascular issues, which could contribute to or complicate POTS.

diagnoses.name: Lupus
diagnoses.description: Systemic lupus erythematosus (SLE) is an autoimmune disease that can affect many parts of the body, including the nervous system, potentially leading to mood lability, cognitive issues, and could be associated with POTS.

diagnoses.name: Sweet's Syndrome
diagnoses.reasoning: Reflects some symptoms like leukocytosis and skin manifestations, but might lack a direct correlation with ulcers and tinnitus.

diagnoses.name: Behcet's Disease
diagnoses.reasoning: Includes symptoms such as ulcers and erythema, along with potential vascular and systemic manifestations like thrombocytosis.

diagnoses.name: Cutaneous Vasculitis
diagnoses.reasoning: Might present with migratory erythema and could indirectly cause symptoms like leukocytosis through systemic inflammation.

diagnoses.name: Erythema Multiforme
diagnoses.reasoning: Characterized by macular lesions, and might feature systemic symptoms, although ulcers are more typically mucosal.

diagnoses.name: Reactive Arthritis
diagnoses.reasoning: Can involve skin and mucosal ulcers, but its direct association with thrombocytosis or leukocytosis would be less specific.

diagnoses.name: Polycythemia Vera
diagnoses.reasoning: A myeloproliferative disorder that can lead to thrombocytosis and erythema but is less likely to directly cause the entire symptom complex.

diagnoses.name: Systemic Lupus Erythematosus (SLE)
diagnoses.reasoning: Could theoretically account for a wide range of symptoms including skin manifestations, blood abnormalities, and possibly tinnitus through CNS involvement.

diagnoses.name: Takayasu Arteritis
diagnoses.reasoning: While more rare, it could conceivably be linked to vascular and systemic issues leading to symptoms like thrombocytosis and skin changes, though tinnitus and ulcers are less typically reported.

diagnoses.name: Essential Thrombocythemia
diagnoses.reasoning: Primarily explains thrombocytosis, but other symptoms would need secondary explanations; potentially linked through vascular complications.

diagnoses.name: Syphilis
diagnoses.reasoning: Secondary syphilis can present with macular erythema and leukocytosis, and with tertiary involvement could potentially link to ulcerative lesions and systemic symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Chronic Myeloproliferative Disorders
diagnoses.description: A group of conditions that cause blood cells -- platelets, white blood cells, and red blood cells -- to grow abnormally in the bone marrow.

diagnoses.name: Obstructive Sleep Apnea
diagnoses.description: A disorder characterized by repetitive episodes of upper airway obstruction during sleep, leading to reduced or completely stopped airflow despite an ongoing effort to breathe.

diagnoses.name: Allergic Rhinitis
diagnoses.description: An allergic response causing itchy, watery eyes, sneezing, and other similar symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Heart Failure
diagnoses.description: A chronic condition in which the heart doesn't pump blood as well as it should.

diagnoses.name: Hyperthyroidism
diagnoses.description: A condition in which the thyroid gland is overactive and produces excessive amounts of thyroid hormone.

diagnoses.name: Iron Deficiency Anemia
diagnoses.description: A common type of anemia — a condition in which blood lacks adequate healthy red blood cells which are necessary for oxygen to body's tissues.

diagnoses.name: Polycythemia Vera
diagnoses.description: A type of blood cancer that causes the bone marrow to make too many red blood cells.

diagnoses.name: Chronic Obstructive Pulmonary Disease (COPD)
diagnoses.description: A chronic inflammatory lung disease that causes obstructed airflow from the lungs.

diagnoses.name: Essential Thrombocythemia
diagnoses.description: A rare disorder in which your body produces too many platelets, leading to a risk of thrombosis.

diagnoses.name: Rheumatoid Arthritis
diagnoses.description: A chronic inflammatory disorder affecting many joints, including those in the hands and feet.

diagnoses.name: Migraine with Aura
diagnoses.description: A type of headache characterized by visual disturbances (scotoma) followed by a headache that's often accompanied by sensitivity to light, sound, or smells, with symptoms like numbness or weakness.

diagnoses.name: Transient Ischemic Attack (TIA)
diagnoses.description: Often called a mini-stroke, it's a temporary period of symptoms similar to those of a stroke. It can cause headache, numbness or weakness usually on one side of the body, and could include vision changes.

diagnoses.name: Multiple Sclerosis (MS)
diagnoses.description: A disease of the central nervous system that can cause numbness or weakness in one or more limbs, partial or complete loss of vision (scotoma), and may include an episode of prolonged ringing in the ears (tinnitus).

diagnoses.name: Brain Tumor
diagnoses.description: A mass or growth of abnormal cells in the brain. Symptoms can include headaches, numbness or weakness in parts of the body, vision problems such as scotomas, and sometimes tinnitus.

diagnoses.name: Stroke
diagnoses.description: Occurs when the blood supply to part of the brain is interrupted or reduced, preventing brain tissue from getting oxygen and nutrients. Symptoms can include headache, numbness or weakness on one side of the body, and trouble with vision.

diagnoses.name: Meniere's Disease
diagnoses.description: A disorder of the inner ear that can lead to dizzy spells (vertigo) and hearing loss. In most cases, Meniere's disease affects only one ear and can also cause tinnitus and a feeling of fullness in the ear.

diagnoses.name: Acoustic Neuroma
diagnoses.description: A benign tumor that develops on the nerve that connects your ear to your brain. It can cause hearing loss, tinnitus, and imbalance or unsteadiness. Over time, it may also lead to numbness or weakness in the face.

diagnoses.name: Vertebrobasilar Insufficiency
diagnoses.description: A condition resulting from a restricted blood supply to the back of the brain. Symptoms can include headache, weakness, numbness, and visual disturbances like scotomas.

diagnoses.name: Giant Cell Arteritis
diagnoses.description: An inflammatory disease of blood vessels that can cause headaches, vision problems including scotomas, jaw pain, and sometimes symptoms that resemble strokes, such as weakness.

diagnoses.name: Posterior Circulation Stroke
diagnoses.description: A stroke that occurs in the back part of the brain. It affects the body's ability to perform functions like seeing, walking, and swallowing. Symptoms can include vision problems such as scotomas, weakness, numbness, and headache.

A chronic illness involving your central nervous system. The immune system attacks myelin, which is the protective layer around your nerve fibers, leading to delayed response or permanent nerve damage.
Also known as Lou Gehrig's disease, ALS affects nerve cells in the brain and the spinal cord, causing loss of muscle control.
An autoimmune disorder where the immune system attacks the nerves. This leads to weakness, numbness, and tingling, and can eventually result in paralysis.

Occurs when the blood supply to part of your brain is interrupted or reduced, depriving brain tissue of oxygen and nutrients. Symptoms can include sudden numbness, confusion, trouble seeing, walking, and severe headache.
A chronic autoimmune neuromuscular disease that causes weakness in the skeletal muscles responsible for breathing and moving parts of the body, including the arms and legs.
Resulting from damage to the peripheral nerves, this condition often causes weakness, numbness, and pain, usually in your hands and feet.

Also known as cervical osteoarthritis, this condition involves changes to the bones, cartilage, and discs of the neck. It can lead to compression of the spinal cord and nerve roots, causing numbness and weakness in the limbs.

A mass or growth of abnormal cells in your brain. Its symptoms depend on the size, type, and location of the tumor but can include headaches, seizures, and cognitive or sensory deficits like numbness or weakness.
An inflammation of both sides of one section of the spinal cord, leading to various neurological disorders, including paralysis and sensory problems.
A type of nerve damage that can occur with diabetes. It affects the nerves in the legs and feet, leading to numbness, pain, and weakness in these areas.

diagnoses.name: Migraine
diagnoses.details: Migraine headaches can cause severe throbbing pain or a pulsing sensation, usually on one side of the head. It's often accompanied by nausea, vomiting, and extreme sensitivity to light and sound. Migraine attacks can cause significant pain for hours to days and can be so severe that the pain is disabling.

diagnoses.name: Multiple Sclerosis
diagnoses.details: Multiple sclerosis (MS) is a potentially disabling disease of the brain and spinal cord (central nervous system). The immune system attacks the protective sheath (myelin) that covers nerve fibers and causes communication problems between your brain and the rest of your body.

diagnoses.name: Diabetes
diagnoses.details: Diabetes, particularly uncontrolled diabetes, can lead to neuropathy or damage to the nerves. This can cause a sensation of numbness, especially in the extremities. Weakness and other neurological symptoms may also occur.

diagnoses.name: Stroke
diagnoses.details: A stroke occurs when the blood supply to part of your brain is interrupted or reduced, preventing brain tissue from getting oxygen and nutrients. Brain cells begin to die in minutes. A stroke can cause symptoms such as paralysis, speech difficulties, and sudden headache.

diagnoses.name: Transient Ischemic Attack (TIA)
diagnoses.details: Sometimes known as a mini-stroke, a transient ischemic attack is a brief period of symptoms similar to those in a stroke. A TIA usually lasts only a few minutes and doesn't cause permanent damage.

diagnoses.name: Brain Tumor
diagnoses.details: A brain tumor can apply pressure on and distort brain tissue, leading to symptoms such as headaches, speech or vision problems, changes in mood or personality, seizures, and weakness or numbness on one side of the body.

diagnoses.name: Subarachnoid Hemorrhage
diagnoses.details: This is an emergency condition in which bleeding occurs between the brain and the tissues that cover it. It's often signaled at first by a sudden, severe headache, followed by numbness, weakness, and confusion.

diagnoses.name: Vitamin B12 Deficiency
diagnoses.details: Vitamin B12 deficiency can cause various neurological problems, including numbness, weakness, and memory problems. This deficiency can damage the protective sheath that covers your nerves.

diagnoses.name: Peripheral Neuropathy
diagnoses.details: Peripheral neuropathy refers to the conditions that result when nerves that carry messages to and from the brain and spinal cord from and to the rest of the body are damaged or diseased.

diagnoses.name: Hypothyroidism
diagnoses.details: Hypothyroidism, or underactive thyroid, can lead to symptoms like fatigue, weakness, and headaches. Severe, untreated hypothyroidism can cause peripheral neuropathy, or damage to the peripheral nerves that send information back and forth between the brain and spinal cord to the rest of the body.

diagnoses.name: Multiple Sclerosis
diagnoses.description: A chronic illness involving your central nervous system. The immune system attacks myelin, which is the protective layer around your nerve fibers, leading to delayed response or permanent nerve damage.

diagnoses.name: Guillain-Barre Syndrome
diagnoses.description: A rare disorder in which your body's immune system attacks your nerves, leading to muscle weakness and numbness. Rapid onset of these symptoms is typical.

diagnoses.name: Migraine
diagnoses.description: A neurological condition that can cause multiple symptoms. It’s frequently characterized by intense, debilitating headaches. Symptoms may include nausea, vomiting, difficulty speaking, numbness or tingling, and sensitivity to light and sound.

diagnoses.name: Stroke
diagnoses.description: Occurs when the blood supply to part of your brain is interrupted or reduced, preventing brain tissue from getting oxygen and nutrients. Brain cells start to die in minutes. Symptoms can include trouble speaking, paralysis, or numbness of the face, arm, or leg.

diagnoses.name: Transient Ischemic Attack
diagnoses.description: Often called a mini-stroke, a transient ischemic attack is a brief period of symptoms similar to those of a stroke, but usually lasting only a few minutes and causing no permanent damage.

diagnoses.name: Brain Tumor
diagnoses.description: A mass or growth of abnormal cells in your brain. Many different types of brain tumors exist. Some brain tumors are noncancerous (benign), and some brain tumors are cancerous (malignant). Symptoms can include headaches, seizures, and difficulty with balance.

diagnoses.name: Myasthenia Gravis
diagnoses.description: A long-term condition that causes muscle weakness. It commonly affects the muscles that control the eyes and eyelids, facial expressions, chewing, swallowing, and speaking. However, it can also affect the arms, legs, and muscles that control breathing.

diagnoses.name: Lyme Disease
diagnoses.description: Caused by four main species of bacteria. Lyme disease is transmitted by the bite of an infected black-legged tick, commonly known as a deer tick. Symptoms can include fever, headache, fatigue, and a skin rash called erythema migrans. If untreated, infection can spread to joints, the heart, and the nervous system.

diagnoses.name: Amyotrophic Lateral Sclerosis (ALS)
diagnoses.description: Also known as Lou Gehrig’s disease, is a progressive neurodegenerative disease that affects nerve cells in the brain and the spinal cord. Early symptoms include muscle weakness or stiffness. Progression can lead to losing the ability to control the muscles needed to move, speak, eat, and breathe.

diagnoses.name: Botulism
diagnoses.description: A rare but serious illness caused by a toxin that attacks the body’s nerves. Symptoms can include difficulty swallowing or speaking, facial weakness, and paralysis. Botulism can be fatal and requires immediate emergency care.

diagnoses: Evans syndrome (Autoimmune Hemolytic Anemia with Immunologic Thrombocytopenic Purpura)
Viral infections (e.g., Parvovirus B19, Epstein-Barr virus)

diagnoses.name: Systemic Lupus Erythematosus (SLE)
diagnoses.rationale: SLE can present with a wide range of symptoms, including nonscarring alopecia, arthralgia or arthropathy, hemolytic anemia, and peripheral neuropathy due to its autoimmune nature affecting multiple organ systems.

diagnoses.name: Rheumatoid Arthritis
diagnoses.rationale: Although primarily known for joint inflammation and destruction, it can also lead to extra-articular manifestations such as rheumatoid vasculitis, which can cause peripheral neuropathy, and Felty's syndrome, which involves neutropenia and can lead to hemolytic anemia.

diagnoses.name: Sjögren's Syndrome
diagnoses.rationale: An autoimmune disorder that primarily affects exocrine glands but can also cause nonscarring alopecia, peripheral neuropathy due to peripheral nervous system involvement, and hemolytic anemia.

diagnoses.name: Systemic Sclerosis (Scleroderma)
diagnoses.rationale: While Scleroderma is primarily characterized by skin thickening, systemic features can include hemolytic anemia and peripheral neuropathy. Joint involvement can mimic arthropathy.

diagnoses.name: Mixed Connective Tissue Disease (MCTD)
diagnoses.rationale: MCTD features signs and symptoms of several connective tissue diseases, including SLE, Scleroderma, and Polymyositis, and can present with nonscarring alopecia, arthropathy, hemolytic anemia, and peripheral neuropathy.

diagnoses.name: Polyarteritis Nodosa (PAN)
diagnoses.rationale: As a systemic vasculitis affecting medium and small arteries, PAN can lead to peripheral neuropathy and potentially contribute to hemolytic anemia if it involves the vessels of the spleen or bone marrow. Arthralgias are common.

diagnoses.name: Dermatomyositis
diagnoses.rationale: An inflammatory myopathy that can show features of nonscarring alopecia, arthropathy (joint involvement), and potential for hemolytic anemia. Peripheral neuropathy is less common but can occur.

diagnoses.name: Lupus-like Syndrome
diagnoses.rationale: Some drug-induced conditions can mimic SLE, presenting with symptoms like arthropathy, hemolytic anemia, and nonscarring alopecia. Peripheral neuropathy can also be a side effect of the drugs or the condition itself.

diagnoses.name: HIV/AIDS
diagnoses.rationale: HIV can lead to a wide array of symptoms and opportunistic infections that could mimic this presentation, including hemolytic anemia, arthropathy (either directly or via opportunistic infections), nonscarring alopecia (rare but reported), and peripheral neuropathy.

diagnoses.name: Vitamin B12 Deficiency
diagnoses.rationale: Although primarily known for causing megaloblastic anemia, B12 deficiency can also lead to peripheral neuropathy and is implicated in hair changes. While less commonly associated with arthropathy, deficiency states can contribute to joint problems indirectly.

Schizophrenia (for psychosis, if not attributed to lupus CNS involvement)
Tick-borne diseases (e.g., Rocky Mountain spotted fever)

Schizophrenia (for psychosis, if unrelated to other physical symptoms)

Schizophrenia (in the context of Multi-Systemic Disorders influencing psychosis)

diagnoses.name: Systemic Lupus Erythematosus (SLE)
diagnoses.rationale: SLE can cause hemolytic anemia, proteinuria (due to lupus nephritis), and pericarditis. While telangiectasias are less common, lupus can affect the skin in various ways.

diagnoses.name: Mixed Connective Tissue Disease (MCTD)
diagnoses.rationale: MCTD can present with features of multiple connective tissue diseases, including hemolytic anemia, proteinuria, pericarditis, and telangiectasias.

diagnoses.name: Atypical Hemolytic Uremic Syndrome (aHUS)
diagnoses.rationale: aHUS is characterized by hemolytic anemia, acute kidney injury (proteinuria can be a feature), and can involve systemic complications, though pericarditis and telangiectasias are less direct associations.

diagnoses.name: Scleroderma (Systemic Sclerosis)
diagnoses.rationale: Includes systemic features such as telangiectasias and can lead to kidney involvement (proteinuria), and pericarditis. Hemolytic anemia is less commonly associated.

diagnoses.name: Hereditary Hemorrhagic Telangiectasia (HHT)
diagnoses.rationale: HHT primarily causes telangiectasias but is not typically associated with hemolytic anemia, proteinuria, or pericarditis without other underlying conditions.

diagnoses.name: Rheumatoid Arthritis (RA)
diagnoses.rationale: RA can lead to pericarditis and, in severe cases, can lead to anemia, though typically not hemolytic. Proteinuria is uncommon but can occur if renal involvement exists. Telangiectasias are not a typical feature.

diagnoses.name: Paroxysmal Nocturnal Hemoglobinuria (PNH)
diagnoses.rationale: PNH can cause hemolytic anemia but does not typically present with proteinuria, pericarditis, or telangiectasias.

diagnoses.name: Wegener's Granulomatosis (Granulomatosis with polyangiitis)
diagnoses.rationale: Wegener's can cause a broad set of symptoms including kidney problems (proteinuria) and pericarditis. Hemolytic anemia and telangiectasias are less commonly associated.

diagnoses.name: Thrombotic Thrombocytopenic Purpura (TTP)
diagnoses.rationale: TTP can cause hemolytic anemia but is usually not associated with proteinuria, pericarditis, and telangiectasias without other underlying conditions.

diagnoses.name: Evans Syndrome
diagnoses.rationale: Evans Syndrome involves autoimmune hemolytic anemia and other autoimmune phenomena which could theoretically include proteinuria (renal involvement) and pericarditis, although telangiectasias are not directly associated.

diagnoses: Lupus Erythematosus with Secondary Antiphospholipid Antibody Syndrome
Vasculitis (e.g., Granulomatosis with Polyangiitis, Microscopic Polyangiitis)
Vasculitis, such as Granulomatosis with Polyangiitis
